About a year has passed since I first "woke up".[r]
Never—for not a single moment—did I take what happened in that world as a dream.[r]
The amount of memories in my head, their vividness... it was nothing like a dream.[l][r]
Without a doubt, that layered city was a world I experienced firsthand.[r]
I was born there, raised there, ate, slept, <i>lived</i> there... then crashed, wandered, and died there.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

[cm  ]
[tb_start_text mode=3 ]
But at the same time, I also have <t>this</t> life—here, in modern-day Japan.[l][r]
I was born in some rural town, had an unremarkable childhood, and for some reason pursued a degree in aerospace and mechanical engineering. That went by quick... I earned my degree and got hired by the company I work for now.[r]
These memories feel real, too.[r]
Not to mention the fact that my parents—as well as my grandparents—are alive and well back home.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

[cm  ]
[tb_start_text mode=3 ]
So then, I ask myself: which memories are more real?[l][r]
The answer, to me, is that... both are real. It might sound contradictory, but it must be true.[r]
As I kept questioning myself like this, I eventually figured... oh well. What did it matter?[r]
There are, after all, always problems one could never solve—something like Last Thursdayism, perhaps.[l][r]
... but even though I've come to terms with it, there were still certain doubts and sentimental feelings that just wouldn't leave me.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

[cm  ]
[tb_start_text mode=3 ]
I wonder what's become of that city and those girls now.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

[cm  ]
[bg  time="1500"  method="crossfade"  storage="office.jpg"  ]
[tb_start_text mode=3 ]
This particular office is my workplace in this world; a place for me to play my role. A subcontractor for an aircraft manufacturer.[r]
Right now, I'm struggling day and night with a new design team for parts.[l][r]
... It's such a shame. Many of the designs I saw in that world would far surpass the technology here.[l][r]
I feel regretful, looking back to those days. I had only cared about taking off—nothing else mattered to me but flight itself. So much so that I never bothered trying to understand those seemingly theoretical and unusable designs.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

[cm  ]
[tb_start_text mode=3 ]
If I could have understood the principles behind even one of those technologies and brought them to this world, I would have been so rich by now...[l][r]
Oh well... either way, there's no use in dwelling on the impossible. My chest heaved with a sigh, my chair creaking as I leaned back against it.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

[cm  ]
[tb_start_text mode=3 ]
"Hey Ishii! Did you see the email from GA?"[r]
A colleague asks me from the side, dragging me out of my moment of quiet.[l][r]
"What email?" I reply, raising a brow. I'm in no mood to sit here and respond to flowery, fake-sounding mail.[r]
"The one about that weird inquiry from a student. Apparently, they sent the same email to our competitors and partner companies too.[l][r]
From what I skimmed, it might be related to you, Ishii."[r]
... What? Why would I have anything to do with some stupid thing like that? It's probably a scam, anyway![r]
I didn't show it outwardly, but I felt somewhat irritated as I reluctantly logged into the company email. Taking a moment to glare at the incoming mail, I spotted the one that stood out. Is this it?[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

